	        Send us your pictures   ·  Send us your stories Gauteng MEC for Roads and Transport, Ismail Vadi has been
cautiously aware and optimistic that the Gautrain Strike will end soon. In a statement that was released by the Department of Roads
and Transport on Sunday evening, Vadi said the parties had briefed him on the extensive
negations held between the Bombela Operating Company and the United National
Transport Union (UNTU) over the weekend. “It does seem that an agreement is within reach”  Vadi explained. Read more:  FEDUSA
hopeful as Gautrain talks go into Sunday afternoon As it stands, Gautrain striking workers will be consulted today
on the proposed agreement and the situation may be normalized should a mandate
be given by the employees. “The Gauteng provincial Government is pleased that the
parties have gone back to the negotiating table to find one another”, he said. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.  